tly how those negotiations play out. The legal position, as I say, is that the rights and responsibilities of member states, and of course of citizens of those member states, will persist for as long as we are members of the European Union.     Share         Female Genital Mutilation      The edit just sent has not been saved.  The following error was returned:     This content has already been edited and is awaiting review.     Lilian Greenwood (Nottingham South) (Lab)       Share       2.  What steps the Government is taking to increase the number of prosecutions for female genital mutilation. [906000]     Share          The edit just sent has not been saved.  The following error was returned:     This content has already been edited and is awaiting review.     Vicky Foxcroft (Lewisham, Deptford) (Lab)       Share       5.  What steps the Government is taking to increase the number of prosecutions for female genital mutilation. [906004]     Share          The edit just sent has not been saved.  The following error was returned:     This content has already been edited and is awaiting review.     Andrew Gwynne (Denton and Reddish) (Lab)       Share       7.  What steps the Government is taking to increase the number of prosecutions for female genital mutilation. [906006]     Share          The edit just sent has not been saved.  The following error was returned:     This content has already been edited and is awaiting review.     The Solicitor General (Robert Buckland)       Share       The Government significantly strengthened the law via amendments to the Serious Crime Act 2015 to improve protection of victims through lifelong anonymity and to break down barriers to prosecution. The introduction of a mandatory reporting duty for front-line professionals to identify FGM cases of girls under 18 further improves opportunities for safeguarding and prosecution.     Share          The edit just sent has not been saved.  The following error was returned:     This conten